<HEADLINE>
<P>
EDDIE HART DIDN'T HAVE A LOCK ON GOLD MEDAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jim Murray's claim (Feb. 15) that Eddie Hart was a shoo-in for the 100-meter 
dash gold medal at the 1972 Olympics was hardly based on facts. 
</P>
<P>
Murray dismisses Valery Borzov of the Soviet Union as though he were a 
second-rate sprinter, "with fast times at questionable places." 
</P>
<P>
Borzov was ranked fifth in the world in 100 meters in 1969, second in 1970 and 
first in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
Eddie Hart was a fast but inconsistent sprinter. In 1972, he won two out of 
seven races at 100 meters. 
</P>
<P>
Borzov's Olympic victory over Robert Taylor marked the third year in a row he 
defeated the U.S. champion. The experts had no trouble ranking him No. 1 in the 
world for the second year in a row. 
</P>
<P>
KEN MURRAY, West Covina 
</P>
