<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOVIET OFFICIALS WARN PROTESTERS TO KEEP PEACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Warnings of trouble at pro-democracy rallies, expected to attract hundreds of 
thousands Sunday, were issued by Soviet authorities Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Rallies are planned for Moscow, Leningrad, Sverdlovsk in the Urals and Kiev and 
Lvov in the Ukraine, among other cities. They will come ahead of key March 4 
elections that are likely to see many longtime Communist officials swept from 
power. 
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov, in an order marking Armed Forces Day, 
condemned what he said were attempts by extremists to devalue Communist ideals. 
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry said it is placing one-third more police on duty 
nationwide to keep order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
